    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The maximum size of the power set is <m>2^n</m> where <m>n</m> is the number of 
          states in the machine. Where does this come from?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          There is always a choice to be in a state or not.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p>
          There are two choices with each state, wether to be in it or to not be in it. This means that there 
          are two options for each state, making the maximum size of the power set <m>2^n</m>. 
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Create a power set for a FA with the following states: <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <image xml:id="PowerSetMatx2" width="50%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{equation*}
                  \begin{Bmatrix}
                    \{A\}\amp\{A,B\}\amp\{A,C\}\amp\{A,D\}\\
                    \{B\}\amp\{B,C\}\amp\{B,D\}\amp\{A,B,C\}\\
                    \{C\}\amp\{C,D\}\amp\{A,B,D\}\amp\{A,C,D\}\\
                    \{D\}\amp\{B,C,D\}\amp\{A,B,C,D\}\amp\emptyset
                  \end{Bmatrix}
                  \end{equation*}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
